      {
        "idea": "Leverage Coq's built-in automation with custom Hint databases and eauto",
        "description": "Although the current proofs are complete and correct, they are highly manual and step-by-step. By registering the BST constructors and ForallT helper lemmas into a custom Hint database using `Hint Resolve`, we can use `eauto` to automatically discharge many of the structural goals. Furthermore, combining this with `lia` for arithmetic goals via `Hint Extern` will allow the `insert_BST` and `lookup_insert` theorems to be proved in just a few lines of automated tactics. This improves maintainability and readability of the proof script.",
        "what_to_optimize": "code_length and proof maintainability",
        "cautions": "Be careful with `eauto` depth limits, as deeply nested trees might cause automation to hang. Ensure that `lia` is only triggered on arithmetic subgoals to maintain fast compilation times.",
        "approach_type": "coq.tactics.automation"
      },
      {
        "idea": "Utilize Boolean Reflection for arithmetic comparisons",
        "description": "The current proofs use `destruct (k <? k') eqn:...` followed by `apply Nat.ltb_lt in ...` repeatedly. Instead of manual translation between boolean results and propositions, we can use the `reflect` inductive type from Coq's standard library. By applying a view lemma like `Nat.ltb_spec0` (or `Compare_dec` variants), we can directly destruct the comparison into propositional cases (`k < k'` and `k >= k'`). This removes the need for bookkeeping equations and manual `apply` tactics, streamlining the control flow of the proofs.",
        "what_to_optimize": "proof structure and clarity",
        "cautions": "When replacing `destruct eqn:` with boolean reflection, ensure the context is properly updated so that dependent types or subsequent `lia` calls have the correct arithmetic hypotheses available.",
        "approach_type": "coq.tactics.reflection"
      }
